===Etymology===
Partially from {{inh|en|enm|Saxe}}, {{l|enm|Sax}}; from {{inh|en|ang|*Seaxa}} (attested in plural {{m|ang|Seaxan}}), and {{m|enm|Saxoun}}, from {{der|en|fro||*Saxoun}}, {{m|fro|Saxon||Saxon}}, from {{der|en|LL.|Saxonem}}, accusative of {{m|la|Saxo||a Saxon}}, both from {{der|en|gmw-pro|*sahs}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*sahsą||rock, knife}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*sek-||to cut}}. 

{{rel-top|Cognates:}}
Cognate with {{cog|gml|sasse||someone speaking Saxon, i.e. (Middle) Low German}}, {{cog|ang|Seaxa||a Saxon}}, {{cog|goh|Sahso||a Saxon}}, {{cog|is|Saxi||a Saxon}}, {{cog|et|saks||lord; German}}, {{cog|fi|Saksa||Germany}}. Also cognate to {{cog|ang|seax||a knife, hip-knife, an instrument for cutting, a short sword, dirk, dagger}}; more at {{l|en|sax}}. {{rel-bottom}}

